            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Leilani Kai Smith\u2019s name tells the story of two worlds. Born in Honolulu to a Native Hawaiian mother and a white serviceman father from the mainland, her early life was filled with the scent of plumeria and the sound of the ocean. When she was seven, her father\u2019s military career moved the family to San Francisco, a city of fog and concrete that felt a world away from the islands. This move created a quiet, lifelong ache for a connection to the culture she\u2019d left behind.\n\nAfter high school, Leilani enrolled in the Early Childhood Education program at SF State, driven by a natural gift for connecting with children. However, her formal education was cut short when her mother was diagnosed with a terminal illness. Leilani dropped out to become her primary caregiver, a difficult period that solidified her belief in compassion and patience above all else. After her mother\u2019s passing, returning to the structure of university felt impossible. Instead, she took a job as a teacher's aide at a small community preschool.\n\nHer lack of a degree was offset by an innate talent for managing a classroom with warmth and firm kindness. Over fifteen years, she earned certifications and worked her way up, eventually becoming the Lead Teacher at a preschool in the Inner Richmond. Her $62,000 salary requires careful budgeting, but her life is rich in other ways.\n\nLeilani\u2019s days are structured around her 1.1-mile walk to and from work. Her small, rent-controlled apartment, which she has lived in for over a decade, is her sanctuary, filled with plants, books, and photos of her mother. Her social life is a close-knit circle of fellow teachers and old neighborhood friends, with whom she shares dim sum on weekends. She feels a deep, if complicated, love for San Francisco; it\u2019s the city that holds her career and her grief.\n\nHer quiet dream is to bridge her two worlds. She spends her evenings slowly learning the Hawaiian language online and saves diligently for a trip back to Honolulu, not as a tourist, but as a descendant seeking to reconnect. Ultimately, she aspires to open her own small, community-focused preschool, one that weaves principles of *aloha* (love and compassion) and *kuleana* (responsibility) into its curriculum, finally uniting the two halves of her identity."
