        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers standing at the Honolulu airport, age seven, the air thick with jet fumes and farewells. Her mother draped a fresh plumeria lei over her head, the cool petals soft against her skin. \"So you remember the smell of home, *ku\u02bbu pua*,\" she\u2019d whispered. That scent became a phantom limb, an ache for a world she was leaving behind. The memory is the anchor of her identity, a sensory touchstone for the Hawai\u02bbi that lives inside her, fueling her lifelong quest to reconnect.\n\n2.\nIn her early twenties, during the last months of her mother\u2019s illness, Leilani remembers a quiet afternoon holding her mother\u2019s hand. The skin was paper-thin, but the grip was familiar. Her mother, barely lucid, looked at her and faintly hummed an old lullaby from her own childhood. In that moment, Leilani felt the weight of generations settle on her. It wasn't a burden, but a sacred responsibility. This experience solidified her path, teaching her that true education is rooted in compassion and presence, not in lecture halls.\n\n3.\nYears into her career, a four-year-old in her class named Marco would scream every time his parents left. One morning, instead of trying to distract him, Leilani sat quietly on the floor nearby. She simply said, \"It's hard to say goodbye. I know.\" He stopped, looked at her, and crawled into her lap. It was a silent, profound understanding. That moment affirmed her belief that her real gift wasn\u2019t classroom management, but the ability to see and hold space for another person\u2019s heart, a core tenet of *aloha*.\n\n4.\nOn her thirtieth birthday, walking home from a celebratory dim sum with friends, a sudden downpour started. Leilani ducked under an awning on Clement Street, the city lights blurring in the wet pavement. Instead of annoyance, a wave of profound peace washed over her. She watched the cars swish by, saw the familiar faces in the restaurants, and realized this foggy, concrete city was unequivocally hers, too. It wasn't a replacement for Hawai'i, but a complicated, beloved home that held both her grief and her future.\n\n5.\nJust last year, studying late at night, she finally grasped the Hawaiian word *kuleana*\u2014not just as \"responsibility,\" but as a privilege and a spiritual charge. She looked at the photo of her mother on her bookshelf, then at her savings plan for the preschool. The two halves of her life clicked into place. It wasn't just a dream to open a school; it was her *kuleana* to create a space of belonging for children, weaving the lessons of her mother into the fabric of San Francisco."
